@node IML-146 " MSG-146  Subject: Re: transparencies"

Subject: Re: transparencies
Date: Sat, 13 Aug 94 06:00:53 PDT
From: DrGandalf@cup.portal.com

>> All this talk of the genlock button got me thinking maybe that
>>would work.  Make a plane in DETAIL ed, map my vuport pic onto it, with
>>genlock button active, so all 0-value colors in the map would be
>>transparent.  Of course it didn't work.  The map came out looking
>>swell--but the vuport's windows aren't transparent, they're just black.
>
>Mike, I think that the genlock button is used so that an object's color
>can show through the brushmap.  This allows non-square decals.  What I
>think you need is to use a transparency map.  This map will cut a whole
>in your plane by making the filter value 255 in requested areas.

   I suspect the problem that Mike had was that he was not using a color
mapped picture for the map. A 24bit picture has no color zero, so there is
nothing to choose to make transparent. It isn't zero-value colors that get
made transparent, but it actually color zero (i.e., the zeroth color in the
color map). If he changes the image to a 16 color IFF or a HAM, making sure
that the background black is in pallette position zero, it should work. At
least it did in Imagine 2.0, I haven't use 3.0.


     <ELF> - Eric J Fleischer,MD - Dr Gandalf
     DrGandalf@cup.portal.com


